Regio imperio duo sunta. The idea of imperium, destined to be the greatest contribution of Rome to politics, can scarcely have attained a full-grown force in the regal period, though the accounts given by the Roman historians might almost lead us to suppose so. Yet even in embryo it stands for magistracy rather than monarchy‚ for the supreme authority consen-ed (or confirmed) by a formal act of the burgess-body (lex curiata). 1t is in theory unlimited‚ but not irresponsible, nor un- responsive to counsel and custom4. The king who holds it is at once commander, judge‚ and president in chief. And the Romans seem to have realised so clearly what this imperium implied, without reference to the person of the holder, that they preserved its integrity through the transition from monarchy to republic.
